06146nam a2200673Ia 9780691231402DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912314027 a10.1515/97806912314022doi  a(DE-B1597)613957  a(OCoLC)1309051372  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aART0190102bisacsh04a709.51  aLO 89550qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/105526:1 aWu, Hung, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChinese Art and Dynastic Time /cHung Wu. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b241 color + 63 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBollingen Series (General) ;v3500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Models and Patterns -- t1 The Emergence of Dynastic Time in Chinese Art -- t2 Reconfiguring the World. The First Emperor’s Art Projects -- t3 Conflicting Temporalities Heaven’s Mandate and Its Antitheses -- tPart Two Politics and Religion -- t4 Miraculous Icons and Dynastic Time. Narrating Buddhist Images in Medieval China -- t5 Landscape and Dynastic Power. Competing Yue -- tPart Three Past and Present -- t6 Art History and Dynastic Time. Reading Zhang Yanyuan -- t7 Blind Spots of Dynastic Time. The Case of the Liao -- t8 Returning to the Past. Fugu and Dynastic Time -- tPart Four Rupture and Revolution -- t9 Art of Absence. Remnant Subject and Post-dynastic Temporality -- t10 End as Beginning. Dynastic Time and Revolution -- tConclusion. Dynastic Time and Beyond -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tPhoto and Illustration Credits -- tA.W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts 1952–20210 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping look at Chinese art across the millennia that upends traditional perspectives and offers new pathways for art historyThroughout Chinese history, dynastic time—the organization of history through the lens of successive dynasties—has been the dominant mode of narrating the story of Chinese art, even though there has been little examination of this concept in discourse and practice until now. Chinese Art and Dynastic Time uncovers how the development of Chinese art was described in its original cultural, sociopolitical, and artistic contexts, and how these narratives were interwoven with contemporaneous artistic creation. In doing so, leading art historian Wu Hung opens up new pathways for the consideration of not only Chinese art, but also the whole of art history.Wu Hung brings together ten case studies, ranging from the third millennium BCE to the early twentieth century CE, and spanning ritual and religious art, painting, sculpture, the built environment, and popular art in order to examine the deep-rooted patterns in the historical conceptualization of Chinese art. Elucidating the changing notions of dynastic time in various contexts, he also challenges the preoccupation with this concept as the default mode in art historical writing. This critical investigation of dynastic time thus constitutes an essential foundation to pursue new narrative and interpretative frameworks in thinking about art history.Remarkable for the sweep and scope of its arguments and lucid style, Chinese Art and Dynastic Time probes the roots of the collective imagination in Chinese art and frees us from long-held perspectives on how this art should be understood.Published in association with the Center for Advanced Study in the Visual Arts, National Gallery of Art, Washington, DC  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArt, ChinesexHistory. 7aART / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aChinese art, dynasties, dynastic time, art practices, historical discourse on art, histori